Private groups and officials from Tokyo to London to Charleston,

S.C., offered help to the ruptured San Francisco Bay area, but some said relief for the earthquake could drain coffers already strained by previous disasters.
"I know we still have and will have great needs here and charity certainly begins at home," Riley said.
All Salvation Army centers in the Bay Area, including 34 community service centers and scores of other units, have been turned over to the relief effort.
Los Angeles Mayor Tom Bradley sent police and fire investigators to assess damage from the quake, and convened his own emergency council in a special meeting to discuss other possible measures.
